div.p:
Collocations

There are a few collocations meaning ‘to keep a feast/festival’: 

ἑορτὴν ἄγειν (e.g.: Xen., Cyr. 6, 2, 6);

ἑορτὴν ποιεῖν (e.g.: Hdt. 3, 48, 3); 

ἑορτὴν ἑορτάζειν (e.g.: Xen., Atheniensium respublica 3, 2) – the last one can be described as figura etymologica, it occurs in classical authors, but is especially common in later ones.

Proverbs with the word ἑ.: 

κατόπιν ἑορτῆς ἥκειν ‘to have come the day after the fair’ (cf. Pl., Grg. 447a); 

ἀεργοῖς αἰὲν ἑορτά ‘every day's a holiday to those who don't work’ (cf. Theoc. 15.26)
